Blocks.Text: Level sections of renal cortex and medulla (H&E, PAS, Jones methenamine silver stains) is composed of two
portions of renal cortex and medulla with a sample of up to 8 glomeruli, of which 3 glomeruli (38%) are globally
sclerosed. The intact glomeruli show thickening and focal duplication of the glomerular basement membranes,
and Jones silver staining highlights basement membrane vacuolization and "spike" formation. There is also mild
mesangial hypercellularity. There is no evidence of endocapillary hypercellularity, crescent formation, necrosis,
or wire-loop deposits. There is moderate interstitial fibrosis and tubular atrophy involving approximately 40%
of the sampled cortex, with associated mild interstitial inflammation. The arteries show moderate intimal
fibrosis. There is diffuse and focally marked arteriolar hyalinosis.
By direct immunofluorescence (29 glomeruli, of which 21 are globally sclerosed), the glomeruli show granular
capillary wall and mesangial staining for IgG (3+), IgM (1-2+), C3 (trace) and kappa and lambda light chains
(3+ each). There is no glomerular staining for IgA, C1q, fibrinogen, or albumin. There is no staining of the
tubular basement membranes or interstitium. Tubular casts stain for IgA and kappa and lambda light chains.

Examination of a sample of the tissue submitted for electron microscopy (3 of 8 blocks), in Toluidine blue-
stained thick sections, reveals renal cortex with one intact glomerulus. The glomerular and tubulointerstitial
changes are similar to the light microscopic sample. Ultrastructural evaluation of the single glomerulus
demonstrates numerous subepithelial to intramembranous immune type electron dense deposits in various
stages of reabsorption, associated with thickening and remodeling of the glomerular basement membranes and
focal duplication with cellular interposition. There are also occasional mesangial and rare small subendothelial
immune-type electron dense deposits. There are no endothelial tubuloreticular inclusions. There is extensive
